% Module: validate_arch_includes
% Purpose: Cross-validate architecture.json dependency entries against &lt;include&gt; tags in prompts.
% Phase 5: surface drift between declarative architecture dependencies and the module
% prompts the LLM actually pulls in via &lt;include&gt;.

% Dependencies (imported from sibling modules):
%   - .architecture_registry: BUNDLED_SAMPLE_TOPLEVEL_DIRS, extract_modules,
%     find_architecture_for_project, find_project_root
%   - .sync_order: extract_includes_from_file, extract_module_from_include
%   - .architecture_sync (lazy): parse_prompt_tags, _normalize_prompt_filename,
%     build_dependency_resolver
%   - .agentic_sync_runner (lazy): _basename_from_architecture_filename

<pdd.architecture_sync>
    <include select="def:example_parse_tags,def:example_validate_dependencies,def:example_get_entry,def:example_build_dependency_resolver">context/architecture_sync_example.py</include>
</pdd.architecture_sync>
<pdd.architecture_registry>
    <include>context/architecture_registry_example.py</include>
</pdd.architecture_registry>

% ============================================================
% Responsibilities
% ============================================================
% This module provides cross-validation between architecture.json dependency
% declarations and the actual &lt;include&gt; / &lt;pdd-dependency&gt; tags found in prompt files.
% It detects two kinds of drift:
%   1. Forward mismatch: architecture.json lists a dependency on module X, but the
%      prompt file has no &lt;include&gt; or &lt;pdd-dependency&gt; referencing that module's prompt.
%   2. Reverse mismatch: a prompt &lt;include&gt;s another module's prompt, but
%      architecture.json dependencies do not list that module.
%
% Path-qualified modules (F4): comparison keys preserve the directory prefix so
% same-tail module prompts (e.g. ``commands/fix_python.prompt`` and
% ``server/fix_python.prompt``) are treated as distinct nodes. Unqualified
% legacy filenames degrade to their bare stem so flat-layout architectures keep
% working unchanged.
% It also provides a generation-time contract preflight for existing modules:
%   3. Prompt contract/context mismatch: a prompt declares a broad module interface
%      while &lt;include&gt;ing only a selected slice of the existing output source.
%      For existing modules, a partial self-include must cover every declared public
%      symbol that already exists in the output file, or the prompt must use a full
%      self-include. In staged strict mode, when a prompt-local &lt;pdd-interface&gt;
%      declares public symbols already present in the existing output file, the prompt
%      must include the existing module source context at all; no-self-include is a
%      hard failure for that prompt-local contract. Keep legacy prompts without
%      self-includes compatible by default.

% ============================================================
% Internal helpers
% ============================================================

% _path_preserving_module_key(filename: str) -> Optional[str]
%   - Return a path-preserving module key for an include or arch filename. Mirrors
%     ``auto_deps_architecture._path_preserving_module_key`` (F4 third-party codex
%     review). The helper is duplicated here rather than imported because
%     ``auto_deps_architecture`` already imports ``resolve_architecture_prompt_path``
%     from this module — sharing the helper would create a circular import. Both
%     copies MUST stay in sync.
%   - Gate inputs through ``extract_module_from_include`` so non-module references
%     (e.g. ``context/python_preamble.prompt``) return None and remain ignored.
%   - For accepted ``.prompt`` paths, canonicalize via
%     ``architecture_sync._normalize_prompt_filename`` (strip ``./`` and leading
%     ``prompts/``) and derive the basename via
%     ``agentic_sync_runner._basename_from_architecture_filename`` so directory
%     segments are preserved (``"commands/fix_python.prompt"`` -> ``"commands/fix"``,
%     ``"fix_python.prompt"`` -> ``"fix"``).
%   - For accepted non-prompt module references (example ``.py`` files), degrade
%     to the bare-stem ``extract_module_from_include`` result so the long-standing
%     example-path -> module mapping is preserved.
%   - Returns None when no module key can be derived.

% _module_prompt_include_target(include_path: str) -> Optional[str]
%   - Map an &lt;include&gt; path to a path-preserving module key only when it names
%     another module prompt (i.e. path ends with ".prompt"). Returns a directory-
%     qualified key (``"commands/fix"``) when the include is path-qualified, or
%     the bare stem (``"fix"``) for unqualified legacy paths (F4 third-party
%     codex review).
%   - Context/example files (e.g. context/foo_example.py) and non-language-suffix
%     ``.prompt`` files are ignored so validation matches architecture.json, which
%     lists dependencies between module prompts, not every referenced artifact.
%   - Delegates the heavy lifting to ``_path_preserving_module_key``.

% _BUNDLED_SAMPLE_TOPLEVEL_DIRS: FrozenSet[str]
%   - Re-exported from architecture_registry.BUNDLED_SAMPLE_TOPLEVEL_DIRS for
%     back-compat with external imports. The actual skip is enforced inside
%     find_architecture_for_project via the skip_bundled_sample_arch kwarg
%     (default True). The validator forwards skip_bundled_sample_arch=not strict
%     when iterating discovery results; no local post-filter helper exists in this
%     module any more.

% _resolve_architecture_prompt_path(filename: str, project_root: Path) -> Path
%   - Resolve architecture filename to an on-disk path under the project.
%   - If filename starts with "prompts/", resolve directly under project_root.
%   - Otherwise, resolve under project_root / "prompts".
%   - Normalize backslashes to forward slashes and strip leading slashes.

% resolve_architecture_prompt_path(filename: str, project_root: Path) -> Path
%   - Public API wrapper around _resolve_architecture_prompt_path.

% _pdd_dependency_modules(
%     prompt_path: Path,
%     self_mod: str,
%     arch_data: Optional[List[Dict[str, Any]]] = None,
%     *,
%     dep_resolver: Optional[Callable[[str], str]] = None,
%     return_proof: bool = False,
% ) -> Union[set[str], Tuple[set[str], Dict[str, str]]]
%   - Return path-preserving module keys declared via &lt;pdd-dependency&gt; tags in
%     the prompt header.
%   - Per docs/prompting_guide.md, &lt;pdd-dependency&gt; is the authoritative
%     architectural declaration and a module-prompt &lt;include&gt; is ALSO an
%     architecture edge under the union semantics. The forward check accepts
%     either as proof that the prompt has declared the dependency.
%   - Uses parse_prompt_tags from .architecture_sync to extract "dependencies"
%     tags, then keys each entry through _path_preserving_module_key.
%   - Filters out self_mod.
%   - F7 third-party codex review: when ``dep_resolver`` is supplied (preferred,
%     reused across all entries in one validation run) OR when ``arch_data`` is
%     supplied, raw declarations are first run through the resolver so a bare
%     ``&lt;pdd-dependency&gt;fix_python.prompt&lt;/pdd-dependency&gt;`` resolves to its
%     unambiguous path-qualified arch entry (e.g. ``server/fix_python.prompt``)
%     BEFORE path-preserving keying. Without this step a bare declaration would
%     key to ``"fix"`` while the arch dep keys to ``"server/fix"`` and the
%     validator would falsely warn that the prompt is missing a declaration.
%   - F11 third-party codex review: if both are None, no resolution is performed;
%     when only ``arch_data`` is given, build the resolver on demand via
%     ``architecture_sync.build_dependency_resolver(arch_data)``.
%   - PR #1073 finding 2: when ``return_proof`` is True, additionally return a
%     Dict[str, str] mapping each module key to the raw &lt;pdd-dependency&gt; text
%     that produced it (first-occurrence wins). The reverse-drift check uses
%     this so warnings can name the tag the user actually wrote (not the
%     post-resolver arch filename). Default (False) preserves the original
%     set[str]-only return type for callers that just need the keys.
%   - Returns empty result on OSError or empty content (empty set, or
%     (empty set, empty dict) when return_proof=True).

% _IncludeReference dataclass
%   - Fields: path: str, attrs: Dict[str, str].
%   - Property is_interface_mode: True when mode="interface".
%   - Property is_partial: True when select=, lines=, query=, or mode="interface"
%     is present, because those forms do not guarantee full implementation source.

% _extract_include_references(prompt_content: str) -> List[_IncludeReference]
%   - Parse raw &lt;include ...&gt;target&lt;/include&gt; and self-closing
%     &lt;include path="..." /&gt; tags, preserving include attributes.
%   - Match preprocess include grammar:
%       * body path: &lt;include&gt;path.py&lt;/include&gt;
%       * path attribute: &lt;include path="path.py"&gt;ignored_body.py&lt;/include&gt;
%       * self-closing path attribute: &lt;include path="path.py" /&gt;
%   - When path= is present, it takes precedence over body content.
%   - This must parse plain prompt text and not require the prompt to be valid XML.

% _interface_function_names(interface: Any) -> List[str]
%   - Extract public module symbols declared in architecture/prompt interface blocks.
%   - Reads module.functions, module.classes, module.constants, and module.exports.

% _python_top_level_public_symbols(source: str) -> List[str]
%   - Parse Python source with ast and return public top-level functions/classes/constants.
%   - Include class methods as dotted symbols when discovered.
%
% _python_public_symbol_spans(source: str) -> Dict[str, _PythonSymbolSpan]
%   - Parse Python source with ast and return public symbols with 1-based inclusive
%     line spans.
%   - Use the same public symbol shape as _python_top_level_public_symbols.
%
% _symbols_covered_by_line_ranges(source: str, lines_value: str) -> Set[str]
%   - Map deterministic ContentSelector line ranges to public symbols whose full
%     source span is contained in the selected range.
%   - Support the same line syntax as ContentSelector: N, N-M, N-, -M, comma-separated.
%
% _symbols_covered_by_selectors(selectors, existing_symbols, existing_source) -> Set[str]
%   - Map deterministic select= tokens to covered public symbols.
%   - def:name covers that symbol; class:Name covers the class and dotted members.
%   - lines:N-M selectors cover symbols via _symbols_covered_by_line_ranges.
%
% _symbols_covered_by_partial_includes(self_includes, existing_symbols, existing_source)
%   -> tuple[Set[str], List[str]]
%   - Return symbols covered by deterministic implementation-bearing partial
%     self-includes plus explicit unsupported context notes.
%   - select= wins over query=, matching preprocess behavior.
%   - query= without select= is unsupported for this preflight because semantic
%     extraction is non-deterministic and cannot prove symbol coverage.
%   - mode="interface" self-includes do not count as implementation context because
%     interface mode strips bodies.

% validate_prompt_contract_context(
%     prompt_path: Path,
%     output_path: Path,
%     project_root: Path,
%     architecture_path: Optional[Path] = None,
%     prompt_content: Optional[str] = None,
%     require_prompt_local_source_context: bool = False,
% ) -> List[str]
%   - Generation-time preflight used before the LLM is called.
%   - Load declared module symbols from both &lt;pdd-interface&gt; and matching architecture.json.
%   - If the prompt includes the output source file with a full &lt;include&gt;, return [].
%   - If the prompt includes the output source file with select=/lines=/query= or
%     mode="interface", require deterministic implementation context to cover every
%     declared public symbol that already exists in output_path.
%   - If a prompt-local &lt;pdd-interface&gt; declares symbols already present in
%     output_path, the prompt has no self-include of output_path, and
%     require_prompt_local_source_context=True, return a hard failure saying the
%     prompt includes no existing module source context. This staged strict mode
%     catches changed generated prompt/code contracts that would otherwise pass
%     dry-run and fail real sync architecture conformance.
%   - Treat query-only self-includes and mode="interface" self-includes as unsupported
%     partial context and include that reason in the hard-failure message.
%   - Return a hard-failure message when declared existing symbols are missing from
%     partial self-include context.
%   - Return [] for no-self-include prompts when require_prompt_local_source_context
%     is False so current legacy prompts are not broken by this scoped preflight.

% ============================================================
% Core validation function
% ============================================================

% cross_validate_architecture_with_prompt_includes(
%     arch_data: List[Dict[str, Any]],
%     project_root: Path,
% ) -> List[str]
%
% Compare each architecture entry's "dependencies" (as path-preserving module
% keys) with module targets of &lt;include&gt; tags in the corresponding prompt file.
%
% A declared dependency is satisfied if the prompt either &lt;include&gt;s the
% dependency's prompt OR declares it via &lt;pdd-dependency&gt;. Both are
% architecture edges under the union semantics (see prompting_guide.md and
% agentic_sync_identify_modules_LLM.prompt).
%
% The reverse direction (a prompt-declared edge with no matching arch dep)
% warns symmetrically: a module-prompt &lt;include&gt; OR a &lt;pdd-dependency&gt; tag
% that names a module not listed in architecture.json both surface as drift.
% PR #1073 review fix: the prior asymmetric implementation skipped
% &lt;pdd-dependency&gt; drift here on the assumption architecture_sync would
% heal it, but a user running pdd checkup --validate-arch-includes without
% running pdd sync first would never see the drift. Validation must be
% authoritative on its own — both kinds of tag are architecture edges,
% so both must be reported when arch.json omits them.
%
% Non-module includes (docs, preambles, etc.) are ignored via
% _module_prompt_include_target which only accepts ".prompt" paths.
%
% F4 third-party codex review: comparisons use _path_preserving_module_key so
% directory-qualified entries like "commands/fix_python.prompt" and
% "server/fix_python.prompt" stay distinct. Unqualified arch filenames degrade
% to their bare stem so flat-layout architectures still work.
%
% Algorithm:
%   1. Build filename_to_basename mapping for all entries using
%      _path_preserving_module_key (path-preserving, NOT bare-stem).
%   2. Build dep_resolver ONCE per validation run via
%      architecture_sync.build_dependency_resolver(arch_data) (F11 third-party
%      codex review). Reuse the same resolver across every entry's forward check
%      and across every _pdd_dependency_modules call below — never rebuild per
%      entry. This is a precomputed O(1)-per-dep index, not a per-call scan.
%   3. For each entry with a valid filename and module key:
%      a. Resolve prompt path; if file not found, emit a skip warning and continue.
%      b. Extract &lt;include&gt; targets from the prompt file, filter to module-prompt
%         paths (via _module_prompt_include_target). PR #1073 finding 1: BEFORE
%         keying, run each include through dep_resolver(inc) so a bare include
%         like "b_python.prompt" written from a path-qualified prompt
%         ("commands/a_python.prompt") resolves to the unambiguous arch entry
%         ("commands/b_python.prompt"). Without this step the include keys to
%         bare "b" while sync writes "commands/b_python.prompt" (key "commands/b"),
%         producing a false-positive mismatch on a perfectly-synced repo. Key
%         the resolved filename via _path_preserving_module_key, excluding self,
%         and record include_proof[module] = original include path.
%      c. Extract (tag_modules, tag_proof) via _pdd_dependency_modules(...,
%         dep_resolver=dep_resolver, return_proof=True). The proof map carries
%         the raw &lt;pdd-dependency&gt; text so reverse-drift warnings can name
%         the tag the user actually wrote.
%      d. forward_declared = include_modules | tag_modules
%      e. Extract arch_modules from entry's "dependencies" list. F10 third-party
%         codex review: every raw dep string MUST go through dep_resolver(raw_dep)
%         FIRST so stale-but-bare arch entries like ["fix_python.prompt"] resolve
%         to the unambiguous path-qualified filename ("server/fix_python.prompt")
%         before filename_to_basename lookup. PR #1073 finding 2 follow-up:
%         when filename_to_basename has no entry for the resolved dep (the prompt
%         named in the dep is not a tracked arch module), fall back to
%         _path_preserving_module_key(resolved_fn) directly. Both sides of the
%         comparison MUST use the same keying rule, else an arch-declared dep on
%         an untracked module silently vanishes while the SAME dep declared as a
%         &lt;pdd-dependency&gt; sticks in forward_declared and produces a false
%         reverse mismatch.
%      f. For each module in (arch_modules - forward_declared): emit forward
%         mismatch warning including the dependency filename proof if available
%         (preserving the original raw dep string in the message).
%         Warning format: "architecture.json / &lt;include&gt; mismatch: {fn!r} declares
%         dependency on module {d!r}{extra} but the prompt has no &lt;include&gt; or
%         &lt;pdd-dependency&gt; of that module's prompt"
%      g. For each module in (forward_declared - arch_modules): emit reverse
%         mismatch warning. PR #1073 finding 2: the reverse check is symmetric
%         with the forward check — &lt;include&gt; AND &lt;pdd-dependency&gt; drift both
%         fire. Pick the warning text by which proof map carries the module key:
%         include_proof yields "&lt;include&gt;s module" wording; tag_proof yields
%         "declares &lt;pdd-dependency&gt; on module" wording.
%         Include-form: "architecture.json / &lt;include&gt; mismatch: {fn!r}
%         &lt;include&gt;s module {m!r} ({inc_s!r}) but architecture.json dependencies
%         do not list that module"
%         Tag-form: "architecture.json / &lt;include&gt; mismatch: {fn!r} declares
%         &lt;pdd-dependency&gt; on module {m!r}{tag_extra} but architecture.json
%         dependencies do not list that module"
%   4. Return list of warning strings (empty if no mismatches).

% ============================================================
% Collection / aggregation functions
% ============================================================

% collect_architecture_include_validation_warnings(
%     project_root: Path,
%     *,
%     skip_bundled_sample_arch: bool = True,
% ) -> List[str]
%   - Run cross-validation for every architecture.json under project_root.
%   - Uses find_architecture_for_project to discover architecture files.
%   - Each file is validated with its parent directory as the project root for
%     resolving prompts/… paths, so nested packages work.
%   - When skip_bundled_sample_arch is True (default), skips trees like examples/
%     used in the PDD repository.
%   - Loads each architecture.json, extracts modules, calls
%     cross_validate_architecture_with_prompt_includes with base = arch_path.parent.
%   - Prefixes each warning with the arch_path.
%   - Silently skips files with OSError or JSONDecodeError.

% ============================================================
% CLI integration functions
% ============================================================

% list_validate_arch_include_warnings(project_root: Path, *, strict: bool) -> List[str]
%   - Return cross-validation issues for project_root.
%   - When strict is False (default CLI), skip bundled sample trees.
%   - When True, validate those too (useful for maintainer / CI runs).
%   - Delegates to collect_architecture_include_validation_warnings with
%     skip_bundled_sample_arch=not strict.

% run_validate_arch_includes_cli(
%     project_root: Path,
%     *,
%     strict: bool,
%     quiet: bool,
% ) -> None
%   - Print validation messages and exit with code 1 if there are issues.
%   - Used by ``pdd checkup --validate-arch-includes``.
%   - Uses click for output: green "No … mismatches found." when clean,
%     yellow "Warning: …" on stderr for each issue.
%   - Raises click.exceptions.Exit(1) if any warnings found.

% print_architecture_include_validation_warnings(*, quiet: bool, verbose: bool = False) -> None
%   - Print yellow warnings for the current project only when verbose=True and quiet=False.
%   - Uses rich.print with [yellow] markup.
%   - Uses find_project_root() to locate the project.

% ============================================================
% Deliverables
% ============================================================
% Generate a single Python module with:
%   - Module docstring describing Phase 5 cross-validation purpose.
%   - from __future__ import annotations
%   - Imports: ast, json, re, dataclasses.dataclass, pathlib.Path, typing
%     (Any, Callable, Dict, FrozenSet, List, Optional, Set)
%   - Relative imports from .architecture_registry (BUNDLED_SAMPLE_TOPLEVEL_DIRS,
%     extract_modules) and .sync_order (extract_includes_from_file,
%     extract_module_from_include) at top level.
%   - Lazy imports inside functions to avoid circular imports:
%       * click, rich for CLI output
%       * .architecture_registry.find_architecture_for_project,
%         .architecture_registry.find_project_root for discovery
%       * .architecture_sync.parse_prompt_tags for tag extraction
%       * .architecture_sync._normalize_prompt_filename and
%         .architecture_sync.build_dependency_resolver for path-preserving
%         keying and dependency resolution
%       * .agentic_sync_runner._basename_from_architecture_filename for
%         deriving path-qualified module keys
%   - All functions and constants described above with their exact signatures,
%     return types, and behavior.
